{erg/(10 M}_\\odot$), corrected for\nMalmquist bias. Assuming a small spread in progenitor masses, this indicates a\nlarge intrinsic diversity in explosion energy. Moreover, $E/M$ is positively\ncorrelated with the amount of $^{56}\\rm{Ni}$ produced in the explosion, as\npredicted by some recent models of core-collapse SNe. We further present\nseveral empirical correlations. The peak magnitude is correlated with the\ndecline rate ($\\Delta m_{15}$), the decline rate is weakly correlated with the\nrise time, and the rise time is not significantly correlated with the peak\nmagnitude. Faster declining SNe are more luminous and have longer rise times.\nThis limits the possible power sources for such events.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 30 Nov 2015 21:21:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-03-23"}
